  "lagi": {
    "display": "lagi",
    "description": "again / still / more / while — repetition, ongoing actions, and additional quantity",
    "usecases": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Again / repeat",
        "explanation": "Use 'lagi' after a verb to mean 'again' — something happens one more time or is repeated. 'Coba lagi' = 'try again', 'terjadi lagi' = 'it happened again'. Very direct and the most common meaning of lagi. Can also double: 'lagi-lagi' = 'once again (sigh)'.",
        "demo": {
          "context": "A: I missed what you said.",
          "native": "Can you say that again?",
          "spanish": "Bisa bilang lagi?"
        },
        "practice": {
          "context": "Adam: I got the answer wrong again.",
          "english": "Let's try again.",
          "spanish": "Coba lagi yuk.",
          "accepted_translations": ["Coba lagi yuk", "Kita coba lagi", "Ayo coba lagi"],
          "hints": [
            { "native": "try", "learning": "coba" },
            { "native": "again", "learning": "lagi" },
            { "native": "let's", "learning": "yuk / kita / ayo" }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "name": "Still / in progress",
        "explanation": "Place 'lagi' before a verb to say something is currently happening or still going on — like a casual present progressive. 'Lagi makan' = 'currently eating / still eating'. Much more natural in spoken Indonesian than formal present-tense constructions.",
        "demo": {
          "context": "A: Is she available right now?",
          "native": "She's still in a meeting.",
          "spanish": "Dia lagi rapat."
        },
        "practice": {
          "context": "Adam: Can I talk to your dad?",
          "english": "He's busy right now.",
          "spanish": "Dia lagi sibuk.",
          "accepted_translations": ["Dia lagi sibuk", "Bapak lagi sibuk"],
          "hints": [
            { "native": "he / she", "learning": "dia" },
            { "native": "currently / in the middle of", "learning": "lagi" },
            { "native": "busy", "learning": "sibuk" }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": 3,
        "name": "More / another",
        "explanation": "Use 'lagi' after a noun or number to mean 'more' or 'another one'. 'Satu lagi' = 'one more', 'sedikit lagi' = 'a little more'. Works for food, drinks, time, items — anything you want more of. Very versatile in everyday conversation.",
        "demo": {
          "context": "A: Do you want some more rice?",
          "native": "Yes, a little more please.",
          "spanish": "Iya, sedikit lagi."
        },
        "practice": {
          "context": "Adam: Ready to go?",
          "english": "Give me five more minutes.",
          "spanish": "Lima menit lagi.",
